<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="355" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
Abdomen mainly membranous with presence of abdominal tergites and fine pigment spots (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Larva of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B propleural sclerite C tergite of abdominal segment V, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 80 µm (B); 130 µm (C)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712647" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">1A</figureCitation>
). Propleural sclerite with irregular shape (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Larva of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B propleural sclerite C tergite of abdominal segment V, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 80 µm (B); 130 µm (C)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712647" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">1B</figureCitation>
) compared to 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tridentata" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" rank="species" species="tridentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">M. tridentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also the abdomen is wider in appearance. The size of the mature larvae of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. harrisi" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" rank="species" species="harrisi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">M. harrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(2.1 mm) is smaller compared to the other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Harris &amp; Holzenthal" authorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Mejicanotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mejicanotrichia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Mejicanotrichia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The propleural sclerite has the form of a &quot;serrated tooth&quot; unlike the other species of the genus (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Larva of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B propleural sclerite C tergite of abdominal segment V, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 80 µm (B); 130 µm (C)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712647" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">1B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Larva of Mejicanotrichia tridentata (Bueno-Soria &amp; Hamilton, 1986) A habitus, dorsal B propleural sclerite C tergite of abdominal segment V, dorsal. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 65 µm (B); 80 µm (C)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712650" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">4B</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bowles, DE" editor="Malicky, H" journalOrPublisher="Faculty of Sciences, Chiang Mai University, Chiang Mai" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" pagination="43 - 52" refId="B2" refString="Bowles, DE, Harris, SC, Bueno-Soria, J, 1999. An assessment of New World Stactobiini (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae) larvae with new larvae descriptions of Alisotrichia, Mejicanotrichia, and Scelobotrichia. In: Malicky, H, Chantaramongkol, P, Eds., Proceedings of the 9th International Symposium on Trichoptera. Faculty of Sciences, Chiang Mai University, Chiang Mai: 43 - 52" title="An assessment of New World Stactobiini (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae) larvae with new larvae descriptions of Alisotrichia, Mejicanotrichia, and Scelobotrichia." volumeTitle="Proceedings of the 9 th International Symposium on Trichoptera." year="1999">Bowles et al. 1999</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, the abdominal dorsal tergites are wider and shorter than in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. tridentata" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" rank="species" species="tridentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">M. tridentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which exhibits a larger number of setae over the tergites than 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. harrisi" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" rank="species" species="harrisi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">M. harrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712647" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
